{{Infobox stadium | name = Estadio Libertadores de América | image = Estadio Libertadores de America 2014.JPG | fullname = Estadio Libertadores de América | location = [[Avellaneda]], [[Buenos Aires Province|Buenos Aires]], [[Argentina]] | built = | opened = 1928 | renovated = 2009 | expanded = | owner = [[Club Atlético Independiente]] | cost = USD 35 million | operator = [[Club Atlético Independiente]] | surface = Grass | scoreboard = | tenants = [[Club Atlético Independiente]] | seating_capacity = 50.365 | dimensions = }}
The '''Estadio Libertadores de América''' is a [[stadium]] located in [[Avellaneda]], [[Buenos Aires Province]]. It is home to the [[Argentina|Argentine]] [[Association football|football]] club [[Club Atlético Independiente|Independiente]]. The stadium was officially named only as recently as 2005,<ref>[http://encolas.blogspot.com/2005/10/estaba-en-cola-pero-partir-de-hoy.html Estaba en cola... pero a partir de hoy...] {{es icon}}</ref> having been previously known simply as ''Estadio de Independiente'' or ''La Doble Visera de Cemento'' ("The double [[cement]] visor") because of the two rooves overhanging the spectators.
The original stadium, located at Ricardo Bochini 751/83, was built in 1928 and had a capacity of 52,823 with 27,863 seats. ''La Doble Visera'', as it was popularly known, was the first cement stadium built in [[South America]], and would host all international finals Independiente played as local team (7 of the [[Copa Libertadores]], 3 of the [[Intercontinental Cup (football)|Intercontinental Cup]], 2 of the [[Supercopa Sudamericana]] and 2 of the [[Interamerican Cup|Copa Interamericana]]) as well as many Argentina international matches, mostly occurring in the 1930s and 1940s.
==Reconstruction==
In December 2006 the stadium was shuttered, and demolished the following year. The rebuilt stadium was inaugurated on October 28, 2009, in a match against [[Colón de Santa Fe]] of the [[Argentine First Division]] championship ([[2009–10 Primera División Argentina|Apertura 2009]]). The new, European-style stadium has a capacity of roughly 48,069 seats. It also features large digital screens, a restaurant with panoramic view of the pitch, a club museum, offices and conferential facilities, and a shopping centre.<ref>[https://clubaindependiente.com/es/institucion/estadio Website for the new stadium] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140214054359/https://clubaindependiente.com/es/institucion/estadio |date=2014-02-14 }} {{es icon}}</ref>
