{{Infobox cricket ground | ground_name = Officers Club Services Ground | nickname = | country = England | image = | location = [[Aldershot]], [[Hampshire]] | establishment = 1861 | coord = {{coord|51.2603|-0.7713|display=inline}} | seating_capacity = | end1 = | end2 = | year1 = 1906&ndash;present | club1 = [[British Army cricket team|Army]] | year2 = 1905&ndash;1948 | club2 = [[Hampshire County Cricket Club|Hampshire]] | date = 29 December | year = 2011 | source = http://www.cricinfo.com/england/content/ground/56741.html Ground profile }}
The '''Officers Club Services Ground''' is a [[cricket]] ground in Fleet Road, [[Aldershot]], [[Hampshire]], [[England]]. Aldershot had been a small village until 1853, but was transformed following the purchase of 25,000 [[acre]]s of land by the [[War Office]] for military training.<ref name="PRO">{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/england/content/ground/56741.html|title=Ground profile: Officers Club Services Ground|publisher=ESPNcricinfo|accessdate=29 December 2011}}</ref> Over the following two decades Aldershot was transformed into a [[Garrison#British garrison|garrison town]], by 1874 a number of cricket grounds, including the [[Military officers' club|Officers Club]] Services Ground, had been constructed for use by the various regiments garrisoned there.<ref name="PRO"/>
==History== The first recorded match to have been played there was in 1861 between the Knickerbockers and [[I Zingari]]. Over the coming decade the ground was used by the Aldershot Division in matches primarily against I Zingari and the [[Marylebone Cricket Club]], though not exclusively as some matches were against other parts of the armed forces.<ref name="OTH">{{cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Grounds/11/275_misc.html|title=Other matches played on Officers Club Services Ground, Aldershot|publisher=CricketArchive|accessdate=29 December 2011}}</ref> A [[cricket pavilion|pavilion]] was built in 1887.<ref name="PRO"/> [[Hampshire County Cricket Club|Hampshire]] first played [[first-class cricket]] there in the [[1905 County Championship]] against [[Surrey County Cricket Club|Surrey]],<ref name="FCM">{{cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Grounds/11/275_f.html|title=First-Class Matches played on Officers Club Services Ground, Aldershot|publisher=CricketArchive|accessdate=29 December 2011}}</ref> with Hampshire losing this match by 7 wickets.<ref name="SURREY">{{cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/6/6700.html|title=Hampshire v Surrey, 1905 County Championship|publisher=CricketArchive|accessdate=29 December 2011}}</ref> Hampshire used the ground twice more as a venue before [[World War I]], playing Surrey in 1906 and [[Somerset County Cricket Club|Somerset]] in 1910. This season also saw its first-class use by an armed services team, when a combined Army and Navy team played a combined [[Oxford and Cambridge Universities cricket team|Oxford and Cambridge Universities]] team, which marked the final first-class match played there before World War I.<ref name="FCM"/> First-class cricket did not return immediately after the war, the first match of note came in May 1932 when the [[British Army cricket team|Army]] played the touring [[India national cricket team|Indians]] in a two-day non-first-class match, which was abandoned without a ball bowled.<ref name="OTH"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/105/105828.html|title=Army v Indians, 1932|publisher=CricketArchive|accessdate=29 December 2011}}</ref> Later that year in June, first-class cricket returned to the ground when the Army played the touring [[South American cricket team in England in 1932|South Americans]], which the Army won by 5 wickets.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/14/14302.html|title=Army v South Americans, 1932|publisher=CricketArchive|accessdate=29 December 2011}}</ref>
The following season the Army played another first-class match against the touring [[West Indies cricket team|West Indians]], which ended in a draw. Of note was the Army's opening partnership of 286 in their first-innings between [[Reginald Hudson]] and [[Cyril Hamilton]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/14/14835.html|title=Army v West Indians, 1933|publisher=CricketArchive|accessdate=29 December 2011}}</ref> This was the final first-class match held there before [[World War II]],<ref name="FCM"/> despite visits from the touring [[Australia national cricket team|Australians]] in 1934 and 1938, and from the West Indians in 1939, none of which were rated first-class.<ref name="OTH"/> A new pavilion was constructed to replace the original in 1936 and was opened by [[John Francis Gathorne-Hardy|General Sir John Francis Gathorne-Hardy]].<ref name="PRO"/>
Minor matches between various armed services teams and the [[Oxford University Authentics]] were played during the war. Following the end of the war, Hampshire returned to playing first-class cricket at the ground,<ref name="FCM"/> playing two matches in 1948 against [[Cambridge University Cricket Club|Cambridge University]], which was drawn,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/18/18502.html|title=Hampshire v Cambridge University, 1948|publisher=CricketArchive|accessdate=29 December 2011}}</ref> and the [[Combined Services cricket team|Combined Services]], which Hampshire won by an innings and 60 runs.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/18/18511.html|title=Hampshire v Combined Services, 1948|publisher=CricketArchive|accessdate=29 December 2011}}</ref> These matches were the last first-class matches Hampshire would play there. First-class cricket wouldn't return until 1964, when the final first-class held there was played between the Combined Services and [[Oxford University Cricket Club|Oxford University]].<ref name="FCM"/> Both the Army and the Combined Services continued to play at the ground after this, doing so to this day.<ref name="OTH"/> More recently, a [[Women's Twenty20 cricket|Women's Twenty20 International]] was played there in 2011 between [[India women's cricket team|India Women]] and [[New Zealand women's cricket team|New Zealand Women]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Grounds/11/275_witt.html|title=Women's International Twenty-20 Matches played on Officers Club Services Ground, Aldershot|publisher=CricketArchive|accessdate=29 December 2011}}</ref> which India Women won by 3 wickets.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/345/345867.html|title=India Women v New Zealand Women, 2011|publisher=CricketArchive|accessdate=29 December 2011}}</ref>
==Records==
===First-class=== * '''Highest team total:''' 482 by [[Surrey County Cricket Club|Surrey]] v [[Hampshire County Cricket Club|Hampshire]], 1905<ref name="SURREY"/> * '''Lowest team total:''' 99 by [[Combined Services cricket team|Combined Services]] v Hampshire, 1948<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Grounds/11/275/f_Lowest_Team_Totals.html|title=Officers Club Services Ground, Aldershot - Lowest Team Totals in first-class cricket|publisher=CricketArchive|accessdate=29 December 2011}}</ref> * '''Highest individual innings:''' 181 by [[Reginald Hudson]] for [[British Army cricket team|Army]] v [[West Indies cricket team|West Indians]], 1933<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Grounds/11/275/f_Centuries.html|title=Officers Club Services Ground, Aldershot - Centuries in first-class cricket|publisher=CricketArchive|accessdate=29 December 2011}}</ref> * '''Best bowling in an innings:''' 7-45 by [[Charlie Llewellyn]] for Hampshire v [[Somerset County Cricket Club|Somerset]], 1910<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Grounds/11/275/f_Most_Wickets_in_Innings.html|title=Officers Club Services Ground, Aldershot - Seven Wickets in an Innings in first-class cricket|publisher=CricketArchive|accessdate=29 December 2011}}</ref> * '''Best bowling in a match:''' 13-106 by Charlie Llewellyn, as above<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Grounds/11/275/f_Most_Wickets_in_Match.html|title=Officers Club Services Ground, Aldershot - Most Wickets in a Match in first-class cricket|publisher=CricketArchive|accessdate=29 December 2011}}</ref>
